# Theme System Implementation Plan

## Context

T3 Code has an existing light/dark/system mode toggle (`apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts`) that flips a `.dark` CSS class on `<html>`, which Tailwind's `@custom-variant dark` and CSS custom properties in `index.css` respond to. The task is to extend this into a full named-theme system: define theme data in `packages/shared`, refactor the hook, build a selector component with preview swatches, and wire it into the settings page—all without adding dependencies or changing build config.

---

## Step 1 — Create `packages/shared/src/themes.ts`

**New file.** Pure data + lookup functions (no React, no DOM). Follows the `model.ts` pattern.

### Types

```ts
export interface ThemeColors {
  background: string;
  foreground: string;
  card: string;
  cardForeground: string;
  popover: string;
  popoverForeground: string;
  primary: string;
  primaryForeground: string;
  secondary: string;
  secondaryForeground: string;
  muted: string;
  mutedForeground: string;
  accent: string;
  accentForeground: string;
  destructive: string;
  destructiveForeground: string;
  border: string;
  input: string;
  ring: string;
  info: string;
  infoForeground: string;
  success: string;
  successForeground: string;
  warning: string;
  warningForeground: string;
  // Domain-specific surfaces
  sidebar: string;
  sidebarForeground: string;
  editor: string;
  editorForeground: string;
  terminal: string;
  terminalForeground: string;
  statusBar: string;
  statusBarForeground: string;
}

export interface ThemeDefinition {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  /** Controls whether `.dark` class is applied — keeps all existing dark: Tailwind variants working */
  isDark: boolean;
  colors: ThemeColors;
  fontFamily: string;
  fontSize: string;
}
```

### Built-in themes

| Theme | `isDark` | Character |
|---|---|---|
| `t3-dark` | `true` | Current dark palette — resolved literal values matching `@variant dark` in `index.css` |
| `t3-light` | `false` | Current light palette — resolved literal values matching `:root` in `index.css` |
| `t3-midnight` | `true` | Deep blue-black with brighter blue-purple accent; blue-tinted borders/surfaces |

All color values **must** be resolved literals (hex, `oklch(...)`, `rgba(...)`) — not CSS `var()` references — because this module has no DOM context.

- `t3-dark` and `t3-light` use values matching the current `index.css` so applying them is visually identical to the existing behavior.
- `t3-midnight` uses a distinct deep-navy palette for differentiation.
- `fontFamily` defaults to `"DM Sans", -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe UI", system-ui, sans-serif` for all three.
- `fontSize` defaults to `"16px"` for all three.

### Exported functions

```ts
export function listThemes(): ReadonlyArray<ThemeDefinition>
export function getTheme(id: string): ThemeDefinition | undefined
export function getDefaultThemeId(): string              // "t3-dark"
```

### Key file: `packages/shared/src/themes.ts`

---

## Step 2 — Register subpath export

**File: `packages/shared/package.json`**

Add to the `"exports"` object:

```json
"./themes": {
  "types": "./src/themes.ts",
  "import": "./src/themes.ts"
}
```

---

## Step 3 — Add new CSS custom properties to `index.css`

**File: `apps/web/src/index.css`**

The sidebar UI component already references `bg-sidebar` / `text-sidebar-foreground` Tailwind classes (in `components/ui/sidebar.tsx` lines 210, 228) but the CSS variables backing them are **not defined yet**. Add them now, along with editor/terminal/statusBar tokens.

### In the `@theme inline` block, add:

```css
--color-sidebar: var(--sidebar);
--color-sidebar-foreground: var(--sidebar-foreground);
--color-editor: var(--editor);
--color-editor-foreground: var(--editor-foreground);
--color-terminal: var(--terminal);
--color-terminal-foreground: var(--terminal-foreground);
--color-status-bar: var(--status-bar);
--color-status-bar-foreground: var(--status-bar-foreground);
```

### In `:root` (light defaults), add:

```css
--sidebar: var(--card);
--sidebar-foreground: var(--card-foreground);
--editor: var(--background);
--editor-foreground: var(--foreground);
--terminal: var(--background);
--terminal-foreground: var(--foreground);
--status-bar: var(--card);
--status-bar-foreground: var(--card-foreground);
```

### In `@variant dark` inside `:root`, add matching dark overrides:

```css
--sidebar: var(--card);
--sidebar-foreground: var(--card-foreground);
--editor: var(--background);
--editor-foreground: var(--foreground);
--terminal: var(--background);
--terminal-foreground: var(--foreground);
--status-bar: var(--card);
--status-bar-foreground: var(--card-foreground);
```

These CSS defaults serve as the baseline/fallback. When a named theme is active, inline styles on `documentElement` override them.

---

## Step 4 — Refactor `useTheme` hook

**File: `apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts`**

### Design

The hook manages **two** localStorage keys:
- `"t3code:theme"` — mode preference: `"light" | "dark" | "system"` (existing, unchanged)
- `"t3code:color-theme"` — named theme id, e.g. `"t3-midnight"` (new)

### Core logic

1. **Module-load init** (before React): read both keys, resolve theme, apply CSS vars + `.dark` class immediately (prevents flash).
2. **`applyThemeColors(theme: ThemeDefinition)`**: iterates `theme.colors`, converts camelCase keys to kebab-case CSS var names, sets them as inline styles on `document.documentElement.style`. Also sets `--theme-font-family` and `--theme-font-size`. Toggles `.dark` based on `theme.isDark`.
3. **`clearThemeColors()`**: removes all inline style properties so the CSS cascade in `index.css` takes over (used when reverting to default / no explicit theme).
4. **System preference listener**: when mode is `"system"` and no explicit theme-id is stored, auto-select `t3-light` or `t3-dark` based on `prefers-color-scheme`.

### camelCase → kebab-case mapping

`cardForeground` → `--card-foreground`, `statusBar` → `--status-bar`, etc. A simple helper:

```ts
function camelToKebab(s: string): string {
  return s.replace(/[A-Z]/g, (m) => `-${m.toLowerCase()}`);
}
```

### Return type (expanded, backward-compatible)

```ts
{
  /** Mode: "light" | "dark" | "system" */
  theme: Theme;                          // backward-compat alias for mode
  setTheme: (mode: Theme) => void;       // backward-compat alias for setMode
  resolvedTheme: "light" | "dark";       // backward-compat alias — used by DiffPanel, ChatView, ChatMarkdown, DiffWorkerPoolProvider
  /** Named theme */
  themeId: string;
  colorTheme: ThemeDefinition;
  availableThemes: ReadonlyArray<ThemeDefinition>;
  setColorTheme: (id: string) => void;
}
```

**Critical**: `resolvedTheme` must remain `"light" | "dark"` — it's used in 5 components to select diff rendering themes. Derived from `colorTheme.isDark ? "dark" : "light"`.

### Interaction: mode ↔ named theme

- **Picking a named theme** (`setColorTheme`): stores the id in `"t3code:color-theme"`, applies its colors, and syncs the mode key to match (`isDark ? "dark" : "light"`).
- **Switching mode** (`setTheme`): updates `"t3code:theme"`. If no explicit color-theme is stored, auto-selects `t3-light`/`t3-dark`. If an explicit color-theme IS stored but its `isDark` disagrees with the new mode, clear the color-theme key and fall back to auto-selection.
- **"System" mode**: clears `"t3code:color-theme"` and auto-selects based on OS preference.

---

## Step 5 — Create `ThemeSelector` component

**New file: `apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx`**

### Props

```ts
interface ThemeSelectorProps {
  activeThemeId: string;
  themes: ReadonlyArray<ThemeDefinition>;
  onSelect: (themeId: string) => void;
}
```

### Layout

A responsive grid of theme cards. Each card shows:
- A row of 5 color swatch circles: `background`, `primary`, `accent`, `sidebar`, `terminal` from the theme's colors
- The theme name below the swatches
- A "Selected" badge when active (same style as the existing mode radio buttons in settings: `border-primary/60 bg-primary/8`)

Uses only existing UI primitives and Tailwind classes. No new dependencies.

```
┌──────────────────┐  ┌──────────────────┐  ┌──────────────────┐
│  ●  ●  ●  ●  ●   │  │  ●  ●  ●  ●  ●   │  │  ●  ●  ●  ●  ●   │
│  T3 Dark          │  │  T3 Light         │  │  T3 Midnight      │
│         [Selected]│  │                   │  │                   │
└──────────────────┘  └──────────────────┘  └──────────────────┘
```

---

## Step 6 — Update settings page

**File: `apps/web/src/routes/_chat.settings.tsx`**

### Changes

1. Update `useTheme()` destructuring:
   ```ts
   const { theme, setTheme, resolvedTheme, themeId, availableThemes, setColorTheme } = useTheme();
   ```
   (`theme`, `setTheme`, `resolvedTheme` still work via backward-compat aliases)

2. **Keep** the existing Appearance section (System/Light/Dark radio buttons) — these continue to control the mode via `setTheme(option.value)`. No changes to `THEME_OPTIONS` or the radio group markup.

3. **Add** a new "Color Theme" section immediately below the Appearance section:
   ```tsx
   <section className="rounded-2xl border border-border bg-card p-5">
     <div className="mb-4">
       <h2 className="text-sm font-medium text-foreground">Color Theme</h2>
       <p className="mt-1 text-xs text-muted-foreground">
         Choose a color theme for the interface.
       </p>
     </div>
     <ThemeSelector
       activeThemeId={themeId}
       themes={availableThemes}
       onSelect={setColorTheme}
     />
   </section>
   ```

4. Update the "Active theme:" line to also show the theme name:
   ```
   Active mode: dark | Theme: T3 Midnight
   ```

---

## Step 7 — Update sidebar to use theme variable

**File: `apps/web/src/routes/_chat.tsx`** (line 32)

Change `className="border-r border-border bg-card text-foreground"` to `className="border-r border-border bg-sidebar text-sidebar-foreground"` so the sidebar picks up the theme's sidebar colors (now that the CSS variables are defined in Step 3).

---

## Files Modified/Created (Summary)

| File | Action |
|---|---|
| `packages/shared/src/themes.ts` | **Create** — theme types, 3 built-in themes, lookup functions |
| `packages/shared/package.json` | **Edit** — add `"./themes"` subpath export |
| `apps/web/src/index.css` | **Edit** — add sidebar/editor/terminal/statusBar CSS vars in `@theme inline`, `:root`, and `@variant dark` |
| `apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts` | **Edit** — refactor to support named themes + mode, apply CSS custom properties, backward-compat aliases |
| `apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx` | **Create** — theme selector grid with swatch previews |
| `apps/web/src/routes/_chat.settings.tsx` | **Edit** — add Color Theme section with ThemeSelector, update hook usage |
| `apps/web/src/routes/_chat.tsx` | **Edit** — use `bg-sidebar text-sidebar-foreground` on Sidebar |

---

## Verification

1. **`bun typecheck`** — must pass (catches type errors across monorepo)
2. **`bun lint`** — must pass
3. **`bun run test`** — run tests (especially any in packages/shared)
4. **Manual verification**:
   - Fresh load with no localStorage → defaults to `t3-dark`, visually identical to current dark mode
   - Switch to Light mode → applies `t3-light`, visually identical to current light mode
   - Pick T3 Midnight from Color Theme → deep navy palette applies instantly, `.dark` class stays on
   - Switch mode to System → color-theme clears, auto-selects based on OS pref
   - Refresh page → theme persists, no flash of wrong colors
   - Verify `dark:` Tailwind classes still work (check DiffPanel, scrollbar styles)
   - Verify theme applies to sidebar, no visual regression in collapsed/mobile states
   - Cross-tab sync: change theme in one tab, other tab reflects it

